      Are loans securities?
   =20
 =20

The rule in the US is that corporate=C2=A0bonds are =E2=80=9Csecurities=E2=
=80=9D and corporate loans are not. Bonds are subject to the securities law=
s and regulated by the US Securities and Exchange Commission, and if the is=
suer of a bond lies to a buyer then that=E2=80=99s securities fraud. Loans =
are not subject to securities laws, not regulated by the SEC, and lying abo=
ut loans is probably some sort of fraud, but not=C2=A0securities=C2=A0fraud=
.
The traditional reason for this distinction is that bonds could be sold to =
mom-and-pop investors and traded on secondary markets, so you wanted good p=
ublic securities-style disclosure about those bonds, while loans were made =
by banks which held them to maturity. Banks, the theory went, didn=E2=80=99=
t need the protections of securities laws, because they were banks. They we=
re sophisticated lenders who knew their borrowers intimately and got much m=
ore information before making a loan than they would get from a bond prospe=
ctus. And loans were structurally less risky and volatile than bonds: They =
were secured by collateral, so they were safer than unsecured bonds, and th=
e fact that they didn=E2=80=99t trade meant that lenders didn=E2=80=99t usu=
ally have big mark-to-market losses on their loans.
  [1]
=C2=A0Also, on the other side, bonds tended to be issued by big stable inve=
stment-grade companies that could afford to do securities-style disclosure,=
 while banks would often lend money to smaller companies that couldn=E2=80=
=99t.
Everything in that paragraph is a lot less true now than it was 30 years ag=
o. Now, bonds and loans are pretty similar to each other:
=09The investor bases are much more similar. On the bond side, many bonds a=
re sold in private placements
  [2]
=C2=A0limited to institutional investors (asset managers, hedge funds, etc.=
), not retail. On the loan side, many loans are syndicated to institutional=
 investors (hedge funds, collateralized loan obligations, etc.), not banks.=
 And loans are less=C2=A0relationship-driven:=C2=A0A loan is less likely to=
 be made by one bank that knows the borrower well and plans to hold the loa=
n to maturity, and more likely to be made by a group of banks that look lik=
e bond underwriters and go sell the loans to investors.=09The issuer bases =
are much more similar: Investment-grade companies borrow in the bond and lo=
an markets, but so do non-investment-grade companies. Leveraged buyouts are=
 often funded by some mix of bonds and bank loans issued by the same compan=
y.=09The secondary markets are much more similar: Bonds and loans both trad=
e among institutions and are to some extent substitutes for each other.

Bonds are still more often unsecured and fixed-rate, and loans are still mo=
re often secured and floating-rate, but the differences are less prominent.
If you were reimagining the market from scratch, you might say, well, eithe=
r bonds and loans are both securities, or neither of them are, since they a=
re kind of the same things issued by the same companies and traded by the s=
ame investors. Should they both be securities, or neither? I tend to think =
that they should both be securities: They are both investments in companies=
, traded on financial markets=C2=A0by financial institutions, like securiti=
es. Also=C2=A0the Securities Act of 1933  defines =E2=80=9Csecurity=E2=80=
=9D to mean, among other things, =E2=80=9Cany note, =E2=80=A6=C2=A0bond, de=
benture, evidence of indebtedness,=E2=80=9D etc., so bonds are definitely s=
ecurities and it sure sounds like loans (=E2=80=9Cnotes,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9C=
evidences of indebtedness=E2=80=9D) are too. But honestly I don=E2=80=99t f=
eel that strongly about this; both are largely issued in institutional mark=
ets to big investors who can and do demand disclosure even without the prot=
ection of securities laws. Either way would be fine.
But, again, the traditional rule is that bonds are securities and loans are=
n=E2=80=99t. This rule is sometimes cited to a 1990 case called  Reves v. E=
rnst & Young, in which the US Supreme Court said that =E2=80=9Cthe phrase =
=E2=80=98any note=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D in the definition of a security=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9Cshould not be interpreted to mean literally =E2=80=98any note.=E2=
=80=99=E2=80=9D It set out a very woolly test for when a loan is a security=
:
First, we examine the transaction to assess the motivations that would prom=
pt a reasonable seller and buyer to enter into it. If the seller's purpose =
is to raise money for the general use of a business enterprise or to financ=
e substantial investments and the buyer is interested primarily in the prof=
it the note is expected to generate, the instrument is likely to be a "secu=
rity." If the note is exchanged to facilitate the purchase and sale of a mi=
nor asset or consumer good, to correct for the seller's cash-flow difficult=
ies, or to advance some other commercial or consumer purpose, on the other =
hand, the note is less sensibly described as a "security." ... Second, we e=
xamine the "plan of distribution" of the instrument =E2=80=A6=C2=A0to deter=
mine whether it is an instrument in which there is "common trading for spec=
ulation or investment." ... Third, we examine the reasonable expectations o=
f the investing public: The Court will consider instruments to be "securiti=
es" on the basis of such public expectations, even where an economic analys=
is of the circumstances of the particular transaction might suggest that th=
e instruments are not "securities" as used in that transaction. =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0Finally, we examine whether some factor such as the existence of anot=
her regulatory scheme significantly reduces the risk of the instrument, the=
reby rendering application of the Securities Acts unnecessary.
My impression is that nobody has any idea what any of that means, except th=
at they sort of assume =E2=80=9Cwell bank loans are made by banks, which ar=
e regulated by bank regulators, which is =E2=80=98another regulatory regime=
,=E2=80=99 so they=E2=80=99re not securities.=E2=80=9D Though even that isn=
=E2=80=99t true anymore!
Still people occasionally push back on this. In 2014, a=C2=A0company called=
 Millennium Health LLC did a $1.775 billion syndicated term loan; Citigroup=
 Inc. and JPMorgan Chase & Co. led the syndication and sold the loan to 61 =
different lenders. Millennium then got in trouble for some billing fraud, p=
aid a=C2=A0$256 million settlement to the government and filed for bankrupt=
cy in 2015, and a trustee for the lenders sued JPMorgan and Citi for securi=
ties violations. The theory is that the loans were securities, JPMorgan and=
 Citi were underwriters, and they didn=E2=80=99t disclose enough about the =
billing fraud. JPMorgan and Citi moved to dismiss the securities claims, sa=
ying that the loans were not securities. The district court agreed and dism=
issed those claims, the trustee appealed, the case spent years in court,=C2=
=A0the appeals court asked the SEC to weigh in and it  awkwardly declined.=
=C2=A0
Last week, finally,   the banks won on appeal: Corporate loans are still no=
t securities. You can read  the opinion here. It applies the Reves test in =
a way that is even woollier than the original. For instance, was the purpos=
e of Millennium=E2=80=99s term loan =E2=80=9Cinvestment=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=
=9Ccommercial=E2=80=9D? Ehh I dunno whatever:

On the one hand, the pleaded facts plausibly suggest that the lenders=E2=80=
=99 motivation was investment because the lenders expected to profit from t=
heir purchase of the Notes. Under the Credit Agreement, the lenders were en=
titled to receive quarterly interest payments over the course of seven year=
s. They therefore expected to receive a =E2=80=9Cvaluable return=E2=80=9D o=
n their purchase of the Notes.
On the other hand, the pleaded facts do not plausibly suggest that Millenni=
um=E2=80=99s motivation was investment. Millennium was not using the Term L=
oan to raise funds for its urine testing business or to finance other inves=
tments. Instead, it planned to use the Term Loan to pay the outstanding amo=
unt due under the 2012 Credit Agreement, make a shareholder distribution, =
=E2=80=9Credeem outstanding warrants, debentures and stock options,=E2=80=
=9D and pay fees and expenses related to the Transaction.=C2=A0These uses s=
uggest that Millennium=E2=80=99s motivation was commercial.

If a company borrows money to fund its business, that is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9Cinvestment=E2=80=9D? But if it borrows money to pay cash out to share=
holders, that is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=E2=80=9Ccommercial=E2=80=9D? I dunno. Seco=
nd factor:
The pleaded facts do not plausibly suggest that the Notes were =E2=80=9Coff=
ered and sold to a broad segment of the public.=E2=80=9D The Lead Arrangers=
 offered the Notes only to sophisticated institutional entities, providing =
them with a Confidential Information Memorandum.
Yes, they were sold only to institutional investors, same as most bonds. Th=
ird factor:
The pleaded facts do not plausibly suggest that the lenders reasonably perc=
eived the Notes as securities. Instead, we are persuaded that the sophistic=
ated entities that purchased the Notes =E2=80=9Cwere given ample notice tha=
t the [Notes] were . . . loans and not investments in a business enterprise=
.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Before purchasing the Notes, the lenders certified that the=
y were =E2=80=9Csophisticated and experienced in extending credit to entiti=
es similar to [Millennium].=E2=80=9D
Again, same as bonds. Fourth factor:
The pleaded facts do not plausibly suggest that application of securities l=
aws are necessary here for two reasons. First, the Notes were =E2=80=9Csecu=
red by a perfected first priority security interest in all of [Millennium=
=E2=80=99s] tangible and intangible assets,=E2=80=9D i.e., Millennium=E2=80=
=99s collateral. That perfected first priority security interest reduces th=
e risk associated with the Notes. Second, the Office of the Comptroller of =
the Currency, the Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System, and the=
 Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (jointly, the =E2=80=9CBank Regulato=
rs=E2=80=9D) issued =E2=80=9Cspecific policy guidelines=E2=80=9D addressing=
 syndicated term loans.
The stuff about collateral is true, but of course Millennium went bankrupt =
and the lenders lost money, so it=E2=80=99s not=C2=A0that=C2=A0true. The th=
ing that matters here, I think, is the last sentence:=C2=A0Bank regulators=
=C2=A0regulate syndicated loans (even though most of the lenders aren=E2=80=
=99t banks), so=C2=A0securities law=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t have to.
None of this makes very much sense on an intellectual level. On the other h=
and, surely the thinking=C2=A0here =E2=80=94 and probably the reason the SE=
C declined to weigh in =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that the loan market works fine, t=
he bond market works fine, and there=E2=80=99s no reason to change anything=
, and changing the rules of the loan market would, at least in the short te=
rm, cause a lot of disruption. It doesn=E2=80=99t make a ton of sense that =
bonds are securities and loans aren=E2=80=99t, but it doesn=E2=80=99t reall=
y cause much trouble either, so the courts might as well leave it alone.

