   =20
      ESG pay
   =20
 =20

Traditional corporate finance theory says that the sole purpose of the corp=
oration is to maximize profits for shareholders, not because that is=C2=A0t=
he most important thing in the world, but because it is very helpful to pic=
k=C2=A0one=C2=A0thing. Corporations are, for the most part, run by their ex=
ecutives and directors, who mostly choose their own successors without much=
 oversight from shareholders or anyone else. If the rule is =E2=80=9Cexecut=
ives have to maximize profits for shareholders,=E2=80=9D that gives directo=
rs and shareholders and governance activists and everyone else something to=
 measure: If profits are good, then the executives are doing a good job; if=
 they aren=E2=80=99t they aren=E2=80=99t.
If the rule is =E2=80=9Cexecutives have to maximize profits for shareholder=
s, minimize pollution and maximize employee morale,=E2=80=9D then executive=
s and directors have a lot of leeway in=C2=A0measuring=C2=A0their performan=
ce. =E2=80=9CAh well our buddy the CEO didn=E2=80=99t make a lot of money f=
or shareholders=C2=A0this year,=E2=80=9D the directors can say, =E2=80=9Can=
d the pollution is terrible, but surveys show employee satisfaction is up 0=
.3 points on a 7-point scale, so let=E2=80=99s max out her bonus.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0
It is not a law of nature that the board=C2=A0has=C2=A0to do this, of cours=
e. But=C2=A0boards and executives tend to be friendly with each other and n=
ot subject to much outside oversight, and if you don=E2=80=99t give them cl=
ear unambiguous criteria then they might tend to do what is in their intere=
sts rather than what is in the interests of=C2=A0anyone=C2=A0else, sharehol=
ders or employees or the environment. A company answerable for one metric t=
o one set of shareholders has to perform; a company answerable for several =
metrics to several sets of stakeholders can always point to something else.
This is not universally and absolutely true, but it is a useful rule of thu=
mb. It is what I think of, for instance, when I see a bunch of public-compa=
ny chief executive officers saying that the =E2=80=9Cpurpose of a corporati=
on=E2=80=9D is not shareholder value but rather to deliver value to =E2=80=
=9Call stakeholders=E2=80=9D: =E2=80=9COh, right,=E2=80=9D  I think, =E2=80=
=9Cthe CEOs want to be able to brush off shareholder complaints by saying =
=E2=80=98but think of the employees,=E2=80=99 and brush off employee compla=
ints by saying =E2=80=98but think of the community,=E2=80=99 and brush off =
community complaints by saying =E2=80=98but think of the shareholders,=E2=
=80=99 and just do whatever they want.=E2=80=9D A CEO answerable to =E2=80=
=9Call stakeholders=E2=80=9D is answerable to none of them.
Anyway  here=E2=80=99s this:

A growing number of blue-chip US companies are using environmental and soci=
al factors to decide bonuses for top executives, but investors are worried =
the metrics are being gamed to increase payouts.
Three-quarters of S&P 500 companies have disclosed that environmental, soci=
al and governance metrics contributed to executives=E2=80=99 pay, up from t=
wo-thirds of companies in 2021, according to data from The Conference Board=
 and Esgauge, an ESG data analytics firm. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CWe are sceptical of ESG metrics being used in compensation,=E2=80=
=9D said Ben Colton, head of stewardship at State Street Global Advisors, w=
hich manages $3.79tn. =E2=80=9COftentimes they are very subjective, fluffy =
and easily gamed.=E2=80=9D
At Southwest, chief executive Robert Jordan=E2=80=99s pay increased 76 per =
cent to $5.3mn last year even though the airline angered passengers by canc=
elling more than 16,700 flights during the holiday season.
Southwest, in a regulatory filing earlier this year, said the December canc=
ellations negatively affected executives=E2=80=99 bonuses, but added: =E2=
=80=9CWith respect to ESG initiatives, including DEI and sustainability, th=
e [board] determined that the company performed above target-level expectat=
ions.=E2=80=9D DEI stands for diversity, equity and inclusion.

The board can=C2=A0always=C2=A0determine that the company performed above t=
arget-level expectations on DEI initiatives, whereas =E2=80=9Cdid the plane=
s take off?=E2=80=9D is harder to game.

