      SVB wine
   =20
 =20

A few weeks ago, walking down the street in Midtown, I saw someone wearing =
a t-shirt that said =E2=80=9CSilicon Valley Bank Risk Management Department=
, Spring 2023.=E2=80=9D I am pretty sure it was printed as an after-the-fac=
t joke,
  [3]
 just because, if Silicon Valley Bank=E2=80=99s risk management department =
had actually had team t-shirts printed in spring 2023, and you got one, you=
 would not go around wearing it, not because you were embarrassed (though, =
maybe?) but=C2=A0because it would be=C2=A0worth $10,000 on eBay. Few things=
 are more coveted=C2=A0than the relics of failed financial firms. I have an=
 FTX water bottle.=C2=A0
And so if you bought Silicon Valley Bank=E2=80=99s actual wine collection a=
t a Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. auction, and you plan to resell it, sho=
uld you prominently advertise it as being SVB=E2=80=99s wine collection? Ab=
solutely! That wine is far more delicious knowing that it came from a faile=
d bank.  The Wall Street Journal reports:

When [Heritage Auctions wine director Frank]=C2=A0Martell heard through the=
 grapevine that the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. was having the wine auc=
tioned off, he was eager to jump in. After all, a rare-coin company buying =
wine from two collapsed banks seemed, if nothing else, weirdly poetic. ...
After a number of rounds, Martell won the auction for the SVB wine lot for =
roughly $150,000 with fees, a discount of about 40%. Later, he nabbed the m=
ore-than-400-bottle First Republic wine collection for less than $20,000, a=
t about the same discount. Together the collections include bottles with pr=
ice tags that range from $3 to $1,000 a pop.
Martell estimates that Heritage will make tens of thousands of dollars from=
 the two bank wine collections, some of which the company plans to sell at =
its Fine & Rare Wine Signature Auction in Beverly Hills this September. Her=
itage went back and forth over whether to advertise where the wine had come=
 from. It ultimately decided it would.

Correct. SVB was big in the wine lending business, but it doesn=E2=80=99t s=
eem like this wine was seized collateral from loans gone bad; this was just=
 the corporate collection, I think, kept in =E2=80=9Celaborate climate-cont=
rolled cellars built within the bank=E2=80=99s Santa Clara and Menlo Park b=
ranches.=E2=80=9D (Even the $3 bottles?) Anyway the FDIC has fun:

When banks fail, the government can suddenly find itself in charge of =E2=
=80=9Cspecialty assets=E2=80=9D that are extravagant, strange=E2=80=94or ev=
en in flames.=C2=A0
The oddball asset sales are lore within the FDIC. A column in its internal =
newsletter periodically plumbed the history until the author, Jay Rosenstei=
n, retired in 2020, an agency spokesman said. Among the items it recounted:=
 25,000 pounds of frozen rabbit, a 12% share in the Dallas Cowboys in the l=
ate 1980s, a coal mine =E2=80=9Cthat was on fire the day the bank was close=
d=E2=80=9D and abandoned churches and synagogues. Once, the FDIC seized a S=
tyrofoam cooler that turned out to be holding a human skull.

Do you think the FDIC put out the fire? I feel like these days you could ma=
ke more money by selling =E2=80=9CFailed Bank=E2=80=99s Coal Mine, Currentl=
y On Fire=E2=80=9D than if you put the fire out. People want a good disaste=
r story!

