<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Are loans securities?</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The rule in the US is that corporate=C2=A0bond=
s are =E2=80=9Csecurities=E2=80=9D and corporate loans are not. Bonds are s=
ubject to the securities laws and regulated by the US Securities and Exchan=
ge Commission, and if the issuer of a bond lies to a buyer then that=E2=80=
=99s securities fraud. Loans are not subject to securities laws, not regula=
ted by the SEC, and lying about loans is probably some sort of fraud, but n=
ot=C2=A0<em>securities=C2=A0</em>fraud.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The traditional reason for this distinction is=
 that bonds could be sold to mom-and-pop investors and traded on secondary =
markets, so you wanted good public securities-style disclosure about those =
bonds, while loans were made by banks which held them to maturity. Banks, t=
he theory went, didn=E2=80=99t need the protections of securities laws, bec=
ause they were banks. They were sophisticated lenders who knew their borrow=
ers intimately and got much more information before making a loan than they=
 would get from a bond prospectus. And loans were structurally less risky a=
nd volatile than bonds: They were secured by collateral, so they were safer=
 than unsecured bonds, and the fact that they didn=E2=80=99t trade meant th=
at lenders didn=E2=80=99t usually have big mark-to-market losses on their l=
oans.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: =
transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Also, on the other side, bonds tended to be issued by big stable =
investment-grade companies that could afford to do securities-style disclos=
ure, while banks would often lend money to smaller companies that couldn=E2=
=80=99t.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Everything in that paragraph is a lot less tru=
e now than it was 30 years ago. Now, bonds and loans are pretty similar to =
each other:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The investor bases are much more simi=
lar. On the bond side, many bonds are sold in private placements<a class=3D=
"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !imp=
ortant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0limited to institutional investors (asset managers, hedge funds, =
etc.), not retail. On the loan side, many loans are syndicated to instituti=
onal investors (hedge funds, collateralized loan obligations, etc.), not ba=
nks. And loans are less=C2=A0<em>relationship-driven:=C2=A0</em>A loan is l=
ess likely to be made by one bank that knows the borrower well and plans to=
 hold the loan to maturity, and more likely to be made by a group of banks =
that look like bond underwriters and go sell the loans to investors.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The issuer bases are much more similar=
: Investment-grade companies borrow in the bond and loan markets, but so do=
 non-investment-grade companies. Leveraged buyouts are often funded by some=
 mix of bonds and bank loans issued by the same company.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The secondary markets are much more similar: Bonds=
 and loans both trade among institutions and are to some extent substitutes=
 for each other.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bonds are still more often unsecured and fixed=
-rate, and loans are still more often secured and floating-rate, but the di=
fferences are less prominent.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you were reimagining the market from scratc=
h, you might say, well, either bonds and loans are both securities, or neit=
her of them are, since they are kind of the same things issued by the same =
companies and traded by the same investors. Should they both be securities,=
 or neither? I tend to think that they should both be securities: They are =
both investments in companies, traded on financial markets=C2=A0by financia=
l institutions, like securities. Also=C2=A0the Securities Act of 1933 <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32533691.258429/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzE1Lzc3Yg/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB79fc9299" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> defines</a> =E2=80=9Csecurity=E2=80=9D to mean, am=
ong other things, =E2=80=9Cany note, =E2=80=A6=C2=A0bond, debenture, eviden=
ce of indebtedness,=E2=80=9D etc., so bonds are definitely securities and i=
t sure sounds like loans (=E2=80=9Cnotes,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cevidences of in=
debtedness=E2=80=9D) are too. But honestly I don=E2=80=99t feel that strong=
ly about this; both are largely issued in institutional markets to big inve=
stors who can and do demand disclosure even without the protection of secur=
ities laws. Either way would be fine.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But, again, the traditional rule is that bonds=
 are securities and loans aren=E2=80=99t. This rule is sometimes cited to a=
 1990 case called <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
32533691.258429/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdXByZW1lLmp1c3RpYS5jb20vY2FzZXMvZmVkZXJhbC91cy8=
0OTQvNTYv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB800ae2fe" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Reves v. Ernst &amp; =
Young</a>, in which the US Supreme Court said that =E2=80=9Cthe phrase =E2=
=80=98any note=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D in the definition of a security=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9Cshould not be interpreted to mean literally =E2=80=98any note.=E2=80=
=99=E2=80=9D It set out a very woolly test for when a loan is a security:</=
p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">First, we examine the transaction =
to assess the motivations that would prompt a reasonable seller and buyer t=
o enter into it. If the seller's purpose is to raise money for the general =
use of a business enterprise or to finance substantial investments and the =
buyer is interested primarily in the profit the note is expected to generat=
e, the instrument is likely to be a "security." If the note is exchanged to=
 facilitate the purchase and sale of a minor asset or consumer good, to cor=
rect for the seller's cash-flow difficulties, or to advance some other comm=
ercial or consumer purpose, on the other hand, the note is less sensibly de=
scribed as a "security." ... Second, we examine the "plan of distribution" =
of the instrument =E2=80=A6=C2=A0to determine whether it is an instrument i=
n which there is "common trading for speculation or investment." ... Third,=
 we examine the reasonable expectations of the investing public: The Court =
will consider instruments to be "securities" on the basis of such public ex=
pectations, even where an economic analysis of the circumstances of the par=
ticular transaction might suggest that the instruments are not "securities"=
 as used in that transaction. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Finally, we examine whether so=
me factor such as the existence of another regulatory scheme significantly =
reduces the risk of the instrument, thereby rendering application of the Se=
curities Acts unnecessary.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My impression is that nobody has any idea what=
 any of that means, except that they sort of assume =E2=80=9Cwell bank loan=
s are made by banks, which are regulated by bank regulators, which is =E2=
=80=98another regulatory regime,=E2=80=99 so they=E2=80=99re not securities=
.=E2=80=9D Though even that isn=E2=80=99t true anymore!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still people occasionally push back on this. I=
n 2014, a=C2=A0company called Millennium Health LLC did a $1.775 billion sy=
ndicated term loan; Citigroup Inc. and JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. led the syn=
dication and sold the loan to 61 different lenders. Millennium then got in =
trouble for some billing fraud, paid a=C2=A0$256 million settlement to the =
government and filed for bankruptcy in 2015, and a trustee for the lenders =
sued JPMorgan and Citi for securities violations. The theory is that the lo=
ans were securities, JPMorgan and Citi were underwriters, and they didn=E2=
=80=99t disclose enough about the billing fraud. JPMorgan and Citi moved to=
 dismiss the securities claims, saying that the loans were not securities. =
The district court agreed and dismissed those claims, the trustee appealed,=
 the case spent years in court,=C2=A0the appeals court asked the SEC to wei=
gh in and it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32533=
691.258429/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS9zZWFyY2g_cT1zZWMra2lyc2NobmVyK3Np=
dGUlM0FibG9vbWJlcmcuY29tJnNjYV9lc3Y9NTYwNjY0ODkyJnJsej0xQzVDSEZBX2VuVVM4MDd=
VUzgwNyZzeHNyZj1BQjVzdEJqSnZjd2g0MjlYYnBaaEF3TlBaemYwQzJQV2JnJTNBMTY5MzIzNT=
Q3MzkyMCZlaT1FYm5zWkxIV044NnI1Tm9QeEx1ZjRBSSZ2ZWQ9MGFoVUtFd2p4b3NiWDBmLUFBe=
FhPRlZrRkhjVGRCeXdRNGRVRENCQSZ1YWN0PTUmb3E9c2VjK2tpcnNjaG5lcitzaXRlJTNBYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbSZnc19scD1FZ3huZDNNdGQybDZMWE5sY25BaUlITmxZeUJyYVhKelkyaHVaWEl=
nYzJsMFpUcGliRzl2YldKbGNtY3VZMjl0U0pJVFVKMERXSklTY0FGNEFKQUJBSmdCZ1FHZ0FhRU=
txZ0VFTVRjdU1yZ0JBOGdCQVBnQkFjSUNDQkFBR0lBRUdMQUR3Z0lIRUFBWUhoaXdBOElDQ1JBQ=
UdBZ1lIaGl3QThJQ0N4QUFHSW9GR0lZREdMQUR3Z0lGRUFBWWdBVENBZ1lRQUJnV0dCN0NBZ2dR=
QUJpS0JSaUdBOElDQlJBaEdLQUJ3Z0lGRUNFWXF3TGlBd1FZQVNCQmlBWUJrQVlGJnNjbGllbnQ=
9Z3dzLXdpei1zZXJw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB931a600a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> awkwardly dec=
lined</a>.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last week, finally, <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32533691.258429/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDgtMjQvanBtb3JnYW4td2lucy1ydWxpbmctdGhhdC1=
sZXZlcmFnZWQtbG9hbnMtYXJlLW5vdC1zZWN1cml0aWVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA4MjgyM19NT05FWV=
NUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzM=
DgyOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3e790fcb" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">  the banks won on appeal</a>: Corporate loans are still not securiti=
es. You can read <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
2533691.258429/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hC=
RmRmeElVL3IyckNSdGs2a3lFNC92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6e18edd8" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 the opinion here</a>. It applies the Reves test in a way that is even wool=
lier than the original. For instance, was the purpose of Millennium=E2=80=
=99s term loan =E2=80=9Cinvestment=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Ccommercial=E2=80=9D=
? Ehh I dunno whatever:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the one hand, the pleaded facts plausibly s=
uggest that the <em>lenders</em>=E2=80=99 motivation was investment because=
 the lenders expected to profit from their purchase of the Notes. Under the=
 Credit Agreement, the lenders were entitled to receive quarterly interest =
payments over the course of seven years. They therefore expected to receive=
 a =E2=80=9Cvaluable return=E2=80=9D on their purchase of the Notes.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, the pleaded facts do not pl=
ausibly suggest that <em>Millennium=E2=80=99s</em> motivation was investmen=
t. Millennium was not using the Term Loan to raise funds for its urine test=
ing business or to finance other investments. Instead, it planned to use th=
e Term Loan to pay the outstanding amount due under the 2012 Credit Agreeme=
nt, make a shareholder distribution, =E2=80=9Credeem outstanding warrants, =
debentures and stock options,=E2=80=9D and pay fees and expenses related to=
 the Transaction.=C2=A0These uses suggest that Millennium=E2=80=99s motivat=
ion was commercial.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If a company borrows money to fund its busines=
s, that is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cinvestment=E2=80=9D? But if it borrows m=
oney to pay cash out to shareholders, that is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=E2=80=9Ccomme=
rcial=E2=80=9D? I dunno. Second factor:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The pleaded facts do not plausibly=
 suggest that the Notes were =E2=80=9Coffered and sold to a broad segment o=
f the public.=E2=80=9D The Lead Arrangers offered the Notes only to sophist=
icated institutional entities, providing them with a Confidential Informati=
on Memorandum.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes, they were sold only to institutional inve=
stors, same as most bonds. Third factor:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The pleaded facts do not plausibly=
 suggest that the lenders reasonably perceived the Notes as securities. Ins=
tead, we are persuaded that the sophisticated entities that purchased the N=
otes =E2=80=9Cwere given ample notice that the [Notes] were . . . loans and=
 not investments in a business enterprise.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Before purchasing =
the Notes, the lenders certified that they were =E2=80=9Csophisticated and =
experienced in extending credit to entities similar to [Millennium].=E2=80=
=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again, same as bonds. Fourth factor:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The pleaded facts do not plausibly=
 suggest that application of securities laws are necessary here for two rea=
sons. First, the Notes were =E2=80=9Csecured by a perfected first priority =
security interest in all of [Millennium=E2=80=99s] tangible and intangible =
assets,=E2=80=9D i.e., Millennium=E2=80=99s collateral. That perfected firs=
t priority security interest reduces the risk associated with the Notes. Se=
cond, the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, the Board of Governors=
 of the Federal Reserve System, and the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporati=
on (jointly, the =E2=80=9CBank Regulators=E2=80=9D) issued =E2=80=9Cspecifi=
c policy guidelines=E2=80=9D addressing syndicated term loans.</p></blockqu=
ote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The stuff about collateral is true, but of cou=
rse Millennium went bankrupt and the lenders lost money, so it=E2=80=99s no=
t=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>true. The thing that matters here, I think, is th=
e last sentence:=C2=A0<em>Bank regulators=C2=A0</em>regulate syndicated loa=
ns (even though most of the lenders aren=E2=80=99t banks), so=C2=A0<em>secu=
rities law=C2=A0</em>doesn=E2=80=99t have to.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">None of this makes very much sense on an intel=
lectual level. On the other hand, surely the thinking=C2=A0here =E2=80=94 a=
nd probably the reason the SEC declined to weigh in =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that =
the loan market works fine, the bond market works fine, and there=E2=80=99s=
 no reason to change anything, and changing the rules of the loan market wo=
uld, at least in the short term, cause a lot of disruption. It doesn=E2=80=
=99t make a ton of sense that bonds are securities and loans aren=E2=80=99t=
, but it doesn=E2=80=99t really cause much trouble either, so the courts mi=
ght as well leave it alone.</p>
