<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Traditional corporate finance theory says that=
 the sole purpose of the corporation is to maximize profits for shareholder=
s, not because that is=C2=A0the most important thing in the world, but beca=
use it is very helpful to pick=C2=A0<em>one=C2=A0</em>thing. Corporations a=
re, for the most part, run by their executives and directors, who mostly ch=
oose their own successors without much oversight from shareholders or anyon=
e else. If the rule is =E2=80=9Cexecutives have to maximize profits for sha=
reholders,=E2=80=9D that gives directors and shareholders and governance ac=
tivists and everyone else something to measure: If profits are good, then t=
he executives are doing a good job; if they aren=E2=80=99t they aren=E2=80=
=99t.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If the rule is =E2=80=9Cexecutives have to max=
imize profits for shareholders, minimize pollution and maximize employee mo=
rale,=E2=80=9D then executives and directors have a lot of leeway in=C2=A0<=
em>measuring=C2=A0</em>their performance. =E2=80=9CAh well our buddy the CE=
O didn=E2=80=99t make a lot of money for shareholders=C2=A0this year,=E2=80=
=9D the directors can say, =E2=80=9Cand the pollution is terrible, but surv=
eys show employee satisfaction is up 0.3 points on a 7-point scale, so let=
=E2=80=99s max out her bonus.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is not a law of nature that the board=C2=A0=
<em>has=C2=A0</em>to do this, of course. But=C2=A0boards and executives ten=
d to be friendly with each other and not subject to much outside oversight,=
 and if you don=E2=80=99t give them clear unambiguous criteria then they mi=
ght tend to do what is in their interests rather than what is in the intere=
sts of=C2=A0<em>anyone=C2=A0</em>else, shareholders or employees or the env=
ironment. A company answerable for one metric to one set of shareholders ha=
s to perform; a company answerable for several metrics to several sets of s=
takeholders can always point to something else.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not universally and absolutely true, b=
ut it is a useful rule of thumb. It is what I think of, for instance, when =
I see a bunch of public-company chief executive officers saying that the =
=E2=80=9Cpurpose of a corporation=E2=80=9D is not shareholder value but rat=
her to deliver value to =E2=80=9Call stakeholders=E2=80=9D: =E2=80=9COh, ri=
ght,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3253=
3691.258429/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS92aWV3L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDg=
tMTkvbWF4aW1pemUtc2hhcmVob2xkZXItdmFsdWUtdG9wLWNlb3MtbWlnaHQtYmUtb3B0aW5nLW=
91dD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwODI4MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY=
2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA4MjgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB425beac4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> I think</a>, =E2=80=9Cthe CEOs want=
 to be able to brush off shareholder complaints by saying =E2=80=98but thin=
k of the employees,=E2=80=99 and brush off employee complaints by saying =
=E2=80=98but think of the community,=E2=80=99 and brush off community compl=
aints by saying =E2=80=98but think of the shareholders,=E2=80=99 and just d=
o whatever they want.=E2=80=9D A CEO answerable to =E2=80=9Call stakeholder=
s=E2=80=9D is answerable to none of them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/32533691.258429/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvMjVhZ=
WQ2MGQtMWRlYi00YTQxLThmMzktMDBjOTI3MDJiNjYz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdc6e46=
5a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> here=E2=80=99s this</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A growing number of blue-chip US companies are=
 using environmental and social factors to decide bonuses for top executive=
s, but investors are worried the metrics are being gamed to increase payout=
s.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Three-quarters of S&amp;P 500 companies have d=
isclosed that environmental, social and governance metrics contributed to e=
xecutives=E2=80=99 pay, up from two-thirds of companies in 2021, according =
to data from The Conference Board and Esgauge, an ESG data analytics firm. =
=E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe are sceptical of ESG metrics being=
 used in compensation,=E2=80=9D said Ben Colton, head of stewardship at Sta=
te Street Global Advisors, which manages $3.79tn. =E2=80=9COftentimes they =
are very subjective, fluffy and easily gamed.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At Southwest, chief executive Robert Jordan=E2=
=80=99s pay increased 76 per cent to $5.3mn last year even though the airli=
ne angered passengers by cancelling more than 16,700 flights during the hol=
iday season.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Southwest, in a regulatory filing earlier this=
 year, said the December cancellations negatively affected executives=E2=80=
=99 bonuses, but added: =E2=80=9CWith respect to ESG initiatives, including=
 DEI and sustainability, the [board] determined that the company performed =
above target-level expectations.=E2=80=9D DEI stands for diversity, equity =
and inclusion.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The board can=C2=A0<em>always=C2=A0</em>determ=
ine that the company performed above target-level expectations on DEI initi=
atives, whereas =E2=80=9Cdid the planes take off?=E2=80=9D is harder to gam=
e.</p>
